{"id":"1704.01767","submitter":"Kazuhiro Kuboki","authors":"Kazuhiro Kuboki and Hiroyuki Yamase","title":"Static spin susceptibility in magnetically ordered states","comments":"19 pages, 8 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B96, 064411 (2017)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.96.064411","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We report that special care is needed when longitudinal magnetic\nsusceptibility is computed in a magnetically ordered phase, especially in\nmetals. We demonstrate this by studying static susceptibility in both a\nferromagnetic and an antiferromagnetic state in the random phase approximation\nto the two-dimensional Hubbard model on a square lattice. In contrast to the\ncase in the disordered phase, a first derivative of the chemical potential (or\nthe density) with respect to a magnetic field does not vanish in a magnetically\nordered phase when the field is applied parallel to the magnetic moment. This\neffect is crucial and should be included when computing magnetic susceptibility\nin the ordered phase, otherwise an unphysical result would be obtained. In\naddition, consequently the magnetic susceptibility becomes different when\ncomputed at a fixed density and a fixed chemical potential in the ordered\nphase. In particular, we cannot employ magnetic susceptibility at a fixed\nchemical potential to describe a system with a fixed density even if the\nchemical potential is tuned to reproduce the correct density.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 Apr 2017 10:05:34 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 8 Aug 2017 04:50:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-08-09"}
